100 Years Ago Today, This is What Was Happening ...

On January 27, 1926, the British government announced a significant increase in coal production to address the ongoing strike that has disrupted supplies across the nation. In the United States, the Senate continued to debate the possibility of a new tax on excess profits, amidst growing economic concerns. Meanwhile, in Germany, Chancellor Wilhelm Marx faced mounting pressure as hyperinflation continued to challenge the Weimar Republics stability.
